I ran full regressions on a workstation overnight. I saw the same failure in seabase/TEST022 that Jenkins did.  Oddly, seabase/TEST028 failed in Jenkins, but in my overnight run, it passed, which suggests some non-determinism. All other suites passed. In any case, I need to debug the seabase test failures.

Learned something just now. TrafDesc objects are allocated using a factory method, TrafAllocateDDLdesc (sqlcat/TrafDDLdesc.cpp). This method has logic to zero out the object if the "space" parameter is non-null. Otherwise it assumes that the memory is already zeroed out. Evidently, this is true for ComSpace objects. My change above made the "space" parameter non-null for non-ComSpace objects. Hence my need for initializers above. And the regression test failures turned out to be evidence of more initializers needed. So, what I should have done was to change the logic in TrafAllocateDDLdesc rather than adding initializers in TrafDDLdesc.h.

The rework properly initializes the TrafDesc objects, removing my reticence concerning that aspect.

Once again, please don't merge yet; I will rerun full regressions on a workstation overnight.

If I understand this correctly, we will not create any new R2.1 artifacts, but you probably do want to update the web site? If so, would it make sense to just make this change in the master branch and update the site?

The policy I am proposing is that we update the web site from only one branch. We use

* the master branch as long as no release is in progress
* the release branch, once it has been forked off the master branch
* we switch back to the master branch immediately after the release, and after updating the site with the final state of the release branch
